Rating: 3
I make this often-- for breakfast, as a lunch box snack, pot lucks. Minimal tweaking makes it even better than written. My mother taught me that a pinch of salt adds depth and complexity to the flavor of anything sweet. And how can you make a cake without vanilla? I add 1 tsp. vanilla extract, and 1/2 tsp. almond extract to the batter, and nutmeg to the cinnamon/sugar sprinkle. I served this at a dinner party, promising my kids leftovers for breakfast. . .but my friends liked it so much, they finished it. Fortunately, it was easy to make another one. Use as much fruit as the cake can hold. If you have any fresh berries on hand, drop them in the spaces between the sliced stone fruit. Yum!

Rating: 2
I used 3 1/2 large nectarines in this recipe. The leftover cake became a soggy mess. Unless you have 8 or some very hungry people to finish this off, you might just throw the rest away. Would much rather have a cobbler or a crumble with the fruit.

Rating: 3
Delicious. The cake is very plain, but the flavor is good. I added 1 tsp of vanilla in addition to the lemon. This would be great with almond extract & maybe orange as well as lemon. The nectarines were great & you could easily add berries to the top. Lots of thick fruit is the key to success here & be careful not to overcook to avoid dryness. My cake was actually more flavorful & moist the morning after I baked it than hot out of the oven. Simple, easy, quick & yummy. Oh, I did not bother with concentric circles, I just packed as many nectarines as I could in there & it looked & tasted great!

